===Etymology 1===
From 16th-century criminal slang, likely from {{m|en|abet}} or {{der|en|ang|bætan||to make {{l|en|better}}}}; or from {{der|en|fro|abeter||to entice}}, from {{m|fro|a-||to}} + {{m|fro|beter||hound on, urge, to bait}}; but in either case ultimately from {{der|en|gem-pro|-}}. More at {{l|en|abet}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|wager}} A [[wager]], an agreement between two parties that a stake (usually money) will be paid by the loser to the winner (the winner being the one who correctly forecast the outcome of an event).
#: {{ux|en|Dylan owes Fletcher $30 from an unsuccessful '''bet'''.}}
# A degree of [[certainty]].
#: {{ux|en|It’s a safe '''bet''' that it will rain tomorrow.}}
#: {{ux|en|There's a decent '''bet''' that we'll be able to reach the top of that hill in an hour.}}
#: {{ux|en|It’s an even '''bet''' that Jim will come top of the maths test tomorrow.}}

